### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe the problem.

I have an existing external API that is built in .NET 8 using controllers and authenticated using a JwtBearer provided by our Single Sign On OIDC server.

In Blazor, running in InteractiveAuto rendering mode, I want to be able to have the user log in via OIDC.

I then want to have access to the ClaimsPrincipal and the access_token in my components regardless of whether they are being rendered on the server or in the wasm client.

This doesn't seem possible currently, but I think Blazor should be handling this case. If Blazor is being split into two applications, then it should handle authentication like this seamlessly.

### Describe the solution you'd like

My current thinking would be to be able to use Blazor something like this...

```cs
// In Blazor/Program.css
builder.Services.AddOidcAuthentication(options => {
  // ... snip config ...
});

// `AddOidcAuthentication` could just be a convenience method that adds everything needed 
// for authentication against OIDC providers, including the cookies

var apiBaseUrl = builder.Configuration["ApiBaseUrl"];
builder.Services.AddHttpClient("my-api-client", client => {
  client.BaseAddress = new Uri(apiBaseUrl, UriKind.Absolute);
}).AddAuthenticationHeaders();
```

```cs
// In Blazor.Client/Program.cs
builder.Services.AddServerAuthetnication();

// The idea here is that AddServerAuthentication handles setting up
// everything needed for the client to have access to the authentication state,
// ClaimsPrincipal and access_token from the server's authentication

var apiBaseUrl = builder.Configuration["ApiBaseUrl"];
builder.Services.AddHttpClient("my-api-client", client => {
  client.BaseAddress = new Uri(apiBaseUrl, UriKind.Absolute);
}).AddAuthenticationHeaders();
```

Then, in my components (in the WASM Blazor.Client project) I should be able to do this:

```cs
@inject IHttpClientFactory Factory

@* ... snip markup ... *@

@code
{
  protected override async Task OnInitializedAsync()
  {
    var client = Factory.CreateClient("my-named-client");
   // Now I can use `client` to make authenticated requests to my API
  }
}
```

This way, it wouldn't matter if the components were being pre-rendered, SSR or Client rendered - it should just work.


Additionally, if I use the CascadingAuthenticationState in my components/pages I should be able to get the `ClaimsPrincipal` from it regardless of where it's being rendered. The same goes for the access token...

```cs
@inject IHttpClientFactory Factory

@* ... snip markup ... *@

@code
{
  [CascadingParameter]
  public Task<AuthenticationState>? AuthState { get; set; }

  protected override async Task OnInitializedAsync()
  {
    var user = (await AuthState)?.User;
    var accessToken = user.GetAccessToken(); // or similar
  }
}
```

### Additional context

I've spent months trying to get the InteractiveAuto rendering mode working in my scenario but have ultimately given up as I was spending more time trying to figure this out than actually building my application.

Every tutorial, course, etc. that I've seen that attempts to touch on Blazor authentication in .NET 8 is either focussed entirely on the server, uses EF Core and Identity that way or just completely glosses over it without giving any useful information on how to use it in this (what should be) relatively simple and common scenario.

Asking for help on forums and Discord has equally yielded no tangible results.

It seems that this is a gap in the design of Blazor currently.

